## 4. How the App Works — Flow Diagrams

### 4.1 Authentication Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant User
    participant React
    participant Express
    participant MongoDB

    User->>React: Fill login form
    React->>Express: POST /api/auth/login {email, password}
    Express->>MongoDB: Find user by email
    MongoDB-->>Express: User document (with hashed password)
    Express->>Express: bcrypt.compare(entered, hashed)
    Express->>Express: Generate JWT token
    Express-->>React: {user data + token}
    React->>React: Store token in localStorage
    React->>React: Update AuthContext
```

### 4.2 Job Application Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Candidate
    participant React
    participant Express
    participant MongoDB

    Candidate->>React: Click "Apply" on job
    React->>Express: POST /api/applications {jobId}
    Note over Express: authMiddleware verifies JWT
    Express->>MongoDB: Fetch Job (for skills, experience)
    Express->>Express: Calculate AI Match Score
    Express->>MongoDB: Create Application document
    MongoDB-->>Express: Saved application
    Express-->>React: {application + scores}
```

### 4.3 Application Status Pipeline

```
Applied → Screening → Interview → Technical → HR → Offer → Hired
  ↘                                                          
   Rejected (can happen from any stage)
```

---

## 5. Key Concepts You Must Know

### 5.1 JWT Authentication
- **What**: JSON Web Token — a signed, encoded string that proves who you are.
- **How**: On login, server creates a token with `jwt.sign({id}, secret, {expiresIn: '30d'})`. Client stores it in `localStorage` and sends it in every request as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`.
- **Middleware**: [authMiddleware.js](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/server/middleware/authMiddleware.js) extracts the token, verifies it with `jwt.verify()`, and attaches the user object to `req.user`.

### 5.2 Password Hashing (bcrypt)
- Passwords are **never stored in plain text**.
- Before saving, a Mongoose `pre('save')` hook hashes the password using `bcrypt.genSalt(10)` + `bcrypt.hash()`.
- On login, `bcrypt.compare()` checks the entered password against the stored hash.
- **Salt rounds = 10** means 2^10 iterations of the hashing algorithm.

### 5.3 Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
- Three roles: `candidate`, `recruiter`, `admin`.
- [roleMiddleware.js](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/server/middleware/roleMiddleware.js) checks `req.user.role` against allowed roles.
- Example: Only recruiters can create jobs; only candidates can apply.
- [ProtectedRoute.jsx](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/client/src/components/ProtectedRoute.jsx) on the frontend hides routes from unauthorized roles.

### 5.4 AI Matching/Scoring Engine
- Scores are calculated when a **candidate applies** and also when a **recruiter views applications**.
- **Three scoring dimensions**:
  - **Skill Score (60% weight)**: % of job's required skills that the candidate has
  - **Experience Score (30% weight)**: If candidate meets required experience = 100, else proportional
  - **Location Score (10% weight)**: 100 if locations match, 0 otherwise
- **Formula**: `matchScore = (skillScore × 0.6) + (experienceScore × 0.3) + (locationScore × 0.1)`

### 5.5 Mongoose ODM
- **ODM** = Object Document Mapper (like ORM but for NoSQL).
- Schemas define the structure of documents: field types, required fields, defaults, validation.
- **Methods**: `pre('save')` hooks, instance methods like [matchPassword()](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/server/models/User.js#61-65).
- **Population**: `.populate('postedBy', 'name email')` replaces an ObjectId with the actual User data.
- **Indexing**: Fields like `email`, `title`, `company` are indexed for faster queries.
- **Compound Index**: `{ job: 1, candidate: 1 }` on Application prevents duplicate applications.

### 5.6 React Context API
- [AuthContext.jsx](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/client/src/context/AuthContext.jsx) uses `createContext()` to share auth state globally.
- Avoids "prop drilling" — any component can call [useAuth()](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/client/src/context/AuthContext.jsx#39-46) to get `user`, `token`, [login()](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/client/src/context/AuthContext.jsx#18-24), [logout()](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/client/src/context/AuthContext.jsx#25-31).
- Uses `localStorage` to persist login across page refreshes.

### 5.7 Axios Interceptors
- **Request interceptor**: Automatically attaches `Bearer <token>` header to every API call.
- **Response interceptor**: If server returns 401 (Unauthorized), auto-clears token and redirects to login.

### 5.8 Vite Proxy
- In development, [vite.config.js](file:///c:/Users/Yash%20Mishra/OneDrive/Desktop/HireFlow_Project/client/vite.config.js) proxies `/api` requests to `http://localhost:5000` (Express server).
- This avoids CORS issues during development.

